It is primarily released from burning fossil fuels such as coal, oil and gas, as well as cement production.
Nitrogen dioxideThe gas nitrogen dioxide (NO2) comes from burning fossil fuels, car exhaust emissions and the use of nitrogen-based fertilisers used in agriculture.
According to the World Health Organization, a third of deaths from stroke, lung cancer and heart disease can be linked to air pollution.
Deaths from pollutionAround seven million people die prematurely because of air pollution every year.
Problems in pregnancyWomen exposed to air pollution before getting pregnant are nearly 20 per cent more likely to have babies with birth defects, research suggested in January 2018.